<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-486-882  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 486 882.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  April 25 1990 n131 p151(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The PC User's Companion.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Boxer, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BooksReview.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   User verdict. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The PC User's CompanionandM;The PC User's Companion is a jungle of a book: it's very dense and some partsare best avoided, but the right person could find it rewarding.andM;It sets out to tell first-time PC users a bit about how all those numbersbecome pretty spreadsheets.andP;  In this respect, it's a resounding success.andM;The author gives a general introduction to computing rather cleverly, bytracing the history of the IBM PC and dealing with all its insides (diskdrives, CPUs and so on) as they appear.andP;  In a similar way, he coversoperating systems, programming languages, word processors, spreadsheets,graphics programs, peripherals and those other machines-IBM-incompatibles.andM;This approach communicates a wealth of information, but i do have a fewgripes.andP;  A bit of weeding could have been done - we can all guess how topronounce WYSIWYG, for example, and there's a trainspotter's guide to thespecifications of every IBM box ever.andP;  Also, the illustrations, which aremostly dot-matrix-printed screen dumps, are appalling.andM;More seriously, the arrival of 486 machines has rendered the book immediatelyoutdated, as will any radical price-cutting among older models.andP;  Anyway, ifyou're going to be forking out on a 486, it's likely you'll know most of theinformation contained in the book.andM;But if you've ever wondered about wait states or been confused byco-processors, you'd do well to grab a copy.andP;  And by the way, the book hasnothing to do with the eponymous fortnightly magazine.andO;</TEXT></DOC>